<TITLE> Wall Street CEOs concede failures </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Jan 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--Top executives of Wall Street's biggest banks each acknowledged broad failures as they testified to a US commission looking into the financial crisis. Top executives of Wall Street's biggest banks - JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs-- each acknowledged broad failures as they testified to a US commission looking into the financial crisis. Goldman Sachs CEO Lloyd Blankfein. SOUNDBITE: Goldman Sachs CEO Lloyd Blankfein saying (English): "While we recognize that credit standards were loosening, we rationalized the reasons with arguments such as the emerging markets were growing more rapidly; the risk mitigants were better; there was more than enough liquidty in the system." In addition, each of the bankers acknowledged mistakes in managing risk from a real estate bubble and subprime mortgages. But JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon said his bank performed exceptionally well during the 2008 financial meltdown. SOUNDBITE: JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon saying (English): "Throughout the financial crisis, we never posted a quarterly loss, we served as a safe-have for depositers, we worked closely with the federal government and we remained an active lender." But JP Morgan Chase and scores of other banks took billions of dollars in bailout money from the federal government, much of it since repaid. And with public fury growing over the cost of those taxpayer bailouts and huge bonuses for Wall Street bankers, JPMorgan's Dimon told the commission there may be legitimate concerns that bonuses contributed to excessive risk tak
